data.content:
Yes! With modern MSTest, you can use `ValueTuple` instead of `object[]` for type-safe, cleaner data-driven tests:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string Input, bool Expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**Benefits:**
- **Type safety** — no boxing/unboxing or casts from `object`
- **Named fields** — tuples document what each value means
- **Compile-time checks** — mismatched types are caught at build time

This requires **MSTest 3.4+**. The test method signature stays the same — MSTest automatically destructures the tuple into the method parameters.
